<subSubSection id="B387B486FFE9FFC61EE9FD167D74FB80" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FB22E70DFFE9FFC61EE9FD167BA6FCE8" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61EE9FD16782BFD55" bold="true" box="[199,315,655,680]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Remarks.</emphasis>
The available material shows a moderate variability in rib number, ranging from 21 to 24. The new species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61F52FD2D7B0EFD30" baseAuthorityName="de Stefani" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[380,542,692,717]" class="Bivalvia" family="Carditidae" genus="Akardita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carditida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="subrevoluta">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61F52FD2D7B0EFD30" box="[380,542,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">A. subrevoluta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by being much larger (up to ca. 
<quantity id="3C654AE8FFE9FFC61DA7FD2D7AC9FD31" box="[905,985,692,717]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" unit="mm" value="45.0">45 mm</quantity>
in length, while 
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61ABAFD2D7C27FD30" baseAuthorityName="de Stefani" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[1172,1335,692,717]" class="Bivalvia" family="Carditidae" genus="Akardita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carditida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="subrevoluta">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61ABAFD2D7C27FD30" box="[1172,1335,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">A. subrevoluta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not exceed 
<quantity id="3C654AE8FFE9FFC61EC3FD4E7851FD0D" box="[237,321,727,752]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" unit="mm" value="25.0">25 mm</quantity>
), markedly more robust, slightly more inequilateral, ventrally more convex, umbo less prominent, and rib number with a limited overlap at 24 ribs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB22E70DFFE9FFC61EE9FC867D6CFC35" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">
The new species resembles the undescribed species from the Pliocene of 
<collectingCountry id="838AA79DFFE9FFC61A2DFC867D75FCC5" box="[1027,1125,799,824]" name="Portugal" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Portugal</collectingCountry>
, here referred to as 
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61B68FC867B4DFCA1" authority="sensu Dollfus &amp; Cotter, 1909" authorityName="Dollfus &amp; Cotter" authorityYear="1909" class="Bivalvia" family="Carditidae" genus="Cardita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carditida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="matheroni">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61B68FC867819FCA0" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Cardita matheroni</emphasis>
sensu 
<bibRefCitation id="9F0C9AFCFFE9FFC61F79FCDD7B4DFCA1" box="[343,605,836,861]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" refId="ref8065" refString="Dollfus, G. S. &amp; Cotter, J. C. B. (1909) Mollusques tertiaires du Portugal. Le Pliocene au nord du Tage (Plaisancien). 1. Pelecypoda. Precedeed'une notice geologique. Imprimerie Nationale, Lisbonne, 103 pp." type="book">Dollfus &amp; Cotter, 1909</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. According to illustrations by 
<bibRefCitation id="9F0C9AFCFFE9FFC61D97FCDD7C88FCA0" box="[953,1432,836,861]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" refId="ref8065" refString="Dollfus, G. S. &amp; Cotter, J. C. B. (1909) Mollusques tertiaires du Portugal. Le Pliocene au nord du Tage (Plaisancien). 1. Pelecypoda. Precedeed'une notice geologique. Imprimerie Nationale, Lisbonne, 103 pp." type="book">
Dollfus &amp; Cotter (1909: pl. 4, figs 21 
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61B4CFCDC7C60FCA1" box="[1378,1392,837,860]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">–</emphasis>
26)
</bibRefCitation>
, the species from 
<collectingCountry id="838AA79DFFE9FFC61F7BFCFE78A4FC7D" box="[341,436,871,896]" name="Portugal" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Portugal</collectingCountry>
has poorly convex ribs without nodulose sculpture. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61AB1FCFE7C46FC7D" authority="Perna &amp; Brunetti &amp; Bella, 2018" authorityName="Perna &amp; Brunetti &amp; Bella" authorityYear="2018" box="[1183,1366,871,896]" class="Bivalvia" family="Carditidae" genus="Akardita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carditida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="iberica" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61AB1FCFE7C46FC7D" box="[1183,1366,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Akardita iberica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="D2DA8664FFE9FFC61B73FCFE7C8CFC7D" box="[1373,1436,871,896]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" rank="species">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61B73FCFE7C8CFC7D" bold="true" box="[1373,1436,871,896]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
by being more rounded in outline and by the occurrence of some particularly deep, irregularly spaced growth striae, in addition to the finer ones. Both species are similar in size, exceeding 
<quantity id="3C654AE8FFE9FFC61D92FC297D1BFC3A" box="[956,1035,944,968]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" unit="mm" value="40.0">40 mm</quantity>
in length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB22E70DFFE9FFC61EE9FC4D7D74FB80" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">
The original 
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61F79FC4D7BADFC11" authority="Mayer, 1871" authorityName="Mayer" authorityYear="1871" box="[343,701,980,1005]" class="Bivalvia" family="Carditidae" genus="Cardita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carditida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="matheroni">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61F79FC4D7B36FC10" box="[343,550,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Cardita matheroni</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="9F0C9AFCFFE9FFC61C03FC4C7BADFC11" box="[557,701,980,1005]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" refId="ref9409" refString="Mayer, K. (1871) Decouverte des couches a Congeries dans le bassin du Rhone. Vierteljahresschrift der Naturforschenden Gesellschaft in Zurich, 16, 185 - 203." type="journal article">Mayer, 1871</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, is from the upper Miocene 
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61DD7FC4C7D73FC11" box="[1017,1123,981,1004]" class="Bivalvia" family="Dreissenidae" genus="Congeria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61DD7FC4C7D73FC11" box="[1017,1123,981,1004]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Congeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
beds in the area of Bollène, southern 
<collectingCountry id="838AA79DFFE9FFC61F2EFC61785CFBF2" box="[256,332,1016,1039]" name="France" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">France</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="9F0C9AFCFFE9FFC61F73FC6178FDFBED" box="[349,493,1016,1040]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" refId="ref9409" refString="Mayer, K. (1871) Decouverte des couches a Congeries dans le bassin du Rhone. Vierteljahresschrift der Naturforschenden Gesellschaft in Zurich, 16, 185 - 203." type="journal article">Mayer 1871</bibRefCitation>
). According to Mayer, his species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61A23FC6E7DFCFBED" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1037,1260,1015,1040]" class="Bivalvia" family="Carditidae" genus="Cardites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carditida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="antiquatus">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61A23FC6E7DFCFBED" box="[1037,1260,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Cardites antiquatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and to 
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61B68FC6E78BDFBC9" authority="Goldfuss, 1840" authorityName="Goldfuss" authorityYear="1840" class="Bivalvia" family="Carditidae" genus="Cardita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carditida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="partschi">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61B68FC6E79E3FBC8" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Cardita partschi</emphasis>
Goldfuss, 1840
</taxonomicName>
. The Miocene 
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61C76FB847BC7FBC8" authorityName="Goldfuss" authorityYear="1840" box="[600,727,1052,1077]" class="Bivalvia" family="Carditidae" genus="Cardita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carditida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="partschi">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61C76FB847BC7FBC8" box="[600,727,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">C. partschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in turn similar to 
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61DE8FB847D76FBC9" box="[966,1126,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61DE8FB847D72FBC9" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[966,1122,1053,1076]" class="Bivalvia" family="Carditidae" genus="Cardites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carditida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="antiquatus">C. antiquatus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
with nodulose ribs (
<bibRefCitation id="9F0C9AFCFFE9FFC61B7CFB8579C3FBA5" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" refId="ref10294" refString="Sieber, R. (1956) Die mittelmiozanen Carditidae und Cardiidae des Wiener Beckens. Mitteilungen der Geologischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 47, 183 - 234." type="journal article">Sieber 1956</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9F0C9AFCFFE9FFC61EF0FBA67865FBA5" box="[222,373,1087,1112]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" refId="ref10173" refString="Schultz, O. (2003) Bivalvia neogenica (Lucinoidea - Mactroidea). In: Piller, W. E. (Ed.), Catalogus fossilium Austriae. Vol. 1. Part 2. Verlag der Osterreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften, Wien, pp. 381 - 690." type="journal article">Schultz 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9F0C9AFCFFE9FFC61FACFBD97B2FFBA5" box="[386,575,1087,1112]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" refId="ref7447" refString="Caze, B., Saint Martin, J. - P., Merle, D. &amp; Saint Martin, S. (2010) Interet des motifs colores residuels des coquilles de mollusques pour la valorisation des sites paleontologiques et des collections: l'exemple du Badenien de Roumanie. In: Saint Martin, J. - P., Saint Martin S., Oaie G. &amp; Seghedi, A. (Eds.), Le patrimoine paleontologique, Des tresors du fond des temps. GeoEcoMar, Bucarest, pp. 27 - 38." type="book chapter">
Caze 
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61FECFBD878E3FBA5" box="[450,499,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">et al</emphasis>
. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="3C9D9C8EFFE9FFC61C7CFBA67D3DFBA5" authority="sensu Fontannes, 1882" authorityName="Fontannes" authorityYear="1882" box="[594,1069,1087,1112]" class="Bivalvia" family="Carditidae" genus="Cardita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carditida" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="matheroni">
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61C7CFBA67A32FBA5" box="[594,802,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Cardita matheroni</emphasis>
sensu 
<bibRefCitation id="9F0C9AFCFFE9FFC61D5EFBD97D3DFBA5" box="[880,1069,1088,1112]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" refId="ref8172" refString="Fontannes, F. (1882) Les mollusques pliocenes de la Vallee du Rhone et du Roussillon. Vol. 2. Acephales. Georg, Lyon, 320 pp." type="book">Fontannes, 1882</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from the Pliocene of the Rhone Valley (
<bibRefCitation id="9F0C9AFCFFE9FFC61EC3FBFD7B84FB81" box="[237,660,1124,1149]" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" refId="ref8172" refString="Fontannes, F. (1882) Les mollusques pliocenes de la Vallee du Rhone et du Roussillon. Vol. 2. Acephales. Georg, Lyon, 320 pp." type="book">
Fontannes 1882: 122, pl. 7, fig 15 
<emphasis id="C9E93B1FFFE9FFC61C47FBFC7B67FB81" box="[617,631,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">–</emphasis>
17
</bibRefCitation>
) seems to be yet another distinct species.
</paragraph>
